SIMPLE: partnership
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Partnership
<hw>Part"ner*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or
condition of being a partner; <as>as, to be in <ex>partnership</ex> with
another; to have <ex>partnership</ex> in the fortunes of a family or a
state.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A division or sharing among partners; joint
possession or interest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rome, that ne'er knew three lordly heads before,⟦br⟧
First fell by fatal <qex>partnership</qex> of power.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He does possession keep,⟦br⟧
And is too wise to hazard <qex>partnership</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An alliance or association of persons for the
prosecution of an undertaking or a business on joint account; a company;
a firm; a house; <as>as, to form a <ex>partnership</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A contract between two or more
competent persons for joining together their money, goods, labor, and
skill, or any or all of them, under an understanding that there shall be
a communion of profit between them, and for the purpose of carrying on a
legal trade, business, or adventure.</def> <rj><au>Kent.</au>
<au>Story.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Community of profit is absolutely essential to, though
not necessarily the test of, a partnership.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>See <er>Fellowship</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 6.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Limited partnership</b></col>, <cd>a form of partnership
in which the firm consists of one or more general partners, jointly and
severally responsible as ordinary partners, and one or more special
partners, who are not liable for the debts of the partnership beyond the
amount of cash they contribute as capital.</cd> -- <col><b>Partnership
in commendam</b></col>, <cd>the title given to the limited partnership
(F. <xex>soci⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧ en commandit⟦eacute⟧</xex>) of the French
law, introduced into the code of Louisiana.</cd> <au>Burrill.</au> --
<col><b>Silent partnership</b></col>, <cd>the relation of partnership
sustained by a person who furnishes capital only.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Partook</ent>⟦br⟧
